Dean at [[University of Guam]] and founder of [[Guam Community College]].\n\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [http://www.uog.edu/ Official website]\n{{Education in Guam}}\n{{Colleges and Universities in U.S. Dependencies}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guam, University Of}}\n[[Category:University of Guam|*]]\n[[Category:Land-grant universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Guam|University of Guam]]\n[[Category:Schools accredited by the Western Association of Schools and Colleges]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1952]]\n[[Category:1952 establishments in Guam]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name              = University of Guam\n|native_name       = Unibetsed\u00e5t Gu\u00e5han\n|native_name_lang  = cha\n|image_name        = \n|image_size        = \n|caption           = Official Seal of the University of Guam\n|latin_name        =\n|other_name        = U.O.G.\n|former_names      = Territorial College of Guam (1952-1963)<br />College of Guam (1963-1968)\n|motto             = ''[[wikt:excelsior|Excelsior]]''\n|motto_lang        = la\n|mottoeng          = Ever Upward\n|tagline           =\n|established       = 1952\n|free_label        = Vision\n|free              = ''Ina, Deskubre, Setbe''<br />To Enlighten, To Discover, To Serve\n|type              = [[Public university|Public]], [[Land-grant university|Land Grant]]\n|affiliation       =\n|endowment         = [[United States dollar|$]]13.5 million <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uog.edu/newsandevents/2005AnnualReport/index.htm|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20070812090919/http://www.uog.edu/newsandevents/2005AnnualReport/index.htm|url-status=dead|title=UOG 2005 Annual Report|archive-date=12 August 2007}}</ref>\n|chairman          = Christopher K. Felix\n|president         = [[Thomas W. Krise]]\n|faculty           = 180\n|students          = 3,904\n|city              = [[Mangilao, Guam|Mangilao]]\n|state             = [[Guam]]\n|country           = United States\n|postcode          = \n|coor              = {{coord|13|26|N|144|48|E|region:GU_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n|address           = \n|campus            = [[Rural area]] <small>(about 161 [[acre]]s)</small>\n|sports            =\n|nickname          = [[Triton (mythology)|Tritons]]\n|colors            = {{color box|#005826}} {{color box|#ffffff}}<ref>[http://www.uogfound.org/uogendowment/2011/12/60thsoon/ ]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429040211/http://www.uogfound.org/uogendowment/2011/12/60thsoon/ |date=29 April 2012 }}</ref><br />Green and white\n|website           = {{URL|http://www.uog.edu}}\n}}\n'''University of Guam''' ({{lang-ch|Unibetsed\u00e5t Gu\u00e5han}}) ('''U.O.G.''') is a public [[land-grant university]] in [[Mangilao, Guam]]. It is accredited by the [[Western Association of Schools and Colleges]] and offers thirty-four degree programs at the undergraduate level and eleven  master's level programs. Of the university's 3,387 students, 94% are of [[Asian people|Asian]]-[[Pacific Islander]] ethnicity and nearly 72% are full-time (fall 2012 figures). A full-time faculty of about 180 supports the university's mission of \"Ina, Diskubre, Setbe\"&mdash; which translates to \"To Enlighten, to Discover, to Serve.\"\n\n== History ==\nUniversity of Guam was founded in 1952 as a two-year teacher-training school known as the '''Territorial College of Guam''', established by Governor [[Carlton Skinner]].<ref name=sfgate>{{cite web| last = Fagan| first = Kevin| authorlink = | title = Carlton Skinner -- broke racial barriers in Navy| publisher = San Francisco Chronicle| date = 29 August 2004| url = http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=%2Fchronicle%2Farchive%2F2004%2F08%2F29%2FBAG858GD2T1.DTL&type=printable| doi = | accessdate =  5 May 2009}}</ref>  In 1960, the college moved to the present campus in the central district of [[Mangilao, Guam|Mangilao]]. In 1965, the college was accredited as a four-year, degree granting institution. By 1968, enrollment had reached 1,800 students while staff and faculty totaled more than 130. It was designated as a [[land grant institution]] by the [[United States Congress]] in 1972.\n\n===Presidents===\n* Antonio C. Yamashita (1964-1970)^\n* [[Pedro C. Sanchez]] (1970\u20131974)\n* Antonio C. Yamashita (1974-1977)^\n* [[Rosa Roberto Carter]] (1977\u20131983)<ref name=pdn>{{cite news|first= |last= |title=Former UOG President Carter Dies |url=http://www.pacificnewscenter.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4332:former-uog-president-carter-dies&catid=45:guam-news&Itemid=156 |work=[[Pacific Daily News]] |publisher= |date=2010-04-13 |access-date=2010-05-02 }}</ref>\n* Jose Q. Cruz (1983-1987)\n* Wilfredo P. Leon Guerrero (1988\u20131993)^\n* John C. Salas (1993\u20131996)\n* Jose T. Nededog (1996\u20132000)\n* Harold L. Allen (2001\u20132008)^\n* [[Robert A. Underwood]] (2008\u20132018)^\n* [[Thomas W. Krise]] (2018\u2013present)<ref>{{cite news|first= |last= |title=New UOG president starts next week |url=http://www.kuam.com/story/38762017/2018/07/30/new-uog-president-starts-next-week |work=[[KUAM News]] |publisher= |date=2018-07-30 |access-date=2018-08-06}}</ref>\n\n^ Indicates President Emeritus status conferred by UOG Board of Regents\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://index.php/|title=Office of the President &#124; University of Guam|website=index.php}}</ref>\n\n== Colleges and schools ==\n[[File:English & Communications Building - University of Guam - DSC00990.JPG|thumb|300px|right|English and Communications Building]]\n[[File:Libraryrivera.jpg|thumb|450px|upright 1.50|RFK Library at sunset]]\n\nThe University of Guam offers [[bachelor's degree]]s in thirty-four areas and [[master's degree]]s in eleven areas:\n\n*College of Liberal Arts and Social Sciences (CLASS)\n**Division of Humanistic Studies\n**Department of Engl